<NOTE>For Release in Year-End Editions</NOTE>
<HEAD>Politics, Tragedy, Triumph: 1988 As It Unfolded</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS Aug. 27 entry to raise Bangladesh death toll to 1,000;
SUBS Oct. 19-25 entry to raise death toll from Joan-Miriam; SUBS
Dec. 7 entry to reflect revised official death toll from earthquake;
ADDS recent events.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of the major events of 1988:
   
   JAN. 2 _ U.S., Canada sign landmark free-trade agreement.
   JAN. 7 _ Record snowfall in the South, record cold across U.S.
   JAN. 28 _ Face-to-face negotiations begin between Contras and
Sandinistas. Polygamist 13-day siege ends in Utah.
   JAN. 30 _ Washington Redskins defeat Denver Broncos 42-10 in
Super Bowl.
   FEB. 3 _ Contra aid voted down by House. Anthony Kennedy
confirmed as Supreme Court justice.
   FEB. 8 _ Dole and Gephardt win Iowa caucuses.
   FEB. 13 _ Winter Olympics open in Calgary.
   FEB. 16 _ Bush and Dukakis win New Hampshire primary.
   FEB. 17 _ Marine Lt. Col. Richard Higgins kidnapped in Lebanon.
   FEB. 21 _ Jimmy Swaggart steps down from pulpit in sex scandal.
   FEB. 23 _ Nationalist protests begin in Soviet Armenia.
   FEB. 25 _ Panama's President Delvalle fails in attempt to fire
armed forces chief Noriega, indicted on drug charges in U.S.
   MARCH 8 _ Super Tuesday: Bush wins 16 of 17 contests, Democratic
results split.
   MARCH 16 _ Poindexter, North, Secord, Hakim indicted on
conspiracy charges in Iran-Contra affair.
   MARCH 23 _ Sandinistas, Contras sign cease-fire agreement.
   MARCH 29 _ Dole drops out of presidential race.
   APRIL 4 _ Arizona Senate convicts, removes Gov. Mecham.
   APRIL 16 _ Khalil al-Wazir, senior PLO commander, assassinated in
Tunisia.
   APRIL 20 _ Two-week Kuwaiti hijacking ends in Algiers.
   APRIL 26 _ Bush clinches Republican nomination with win in
Pennsylvania. In South Korean election, government party loses
legislative majority to opposition groups.
   MAY 3 _ Three French hostages released in Lebanon.
   MAY 4 _ Deadline for illegal aliens in U.S. to apply for amnesty.
   MAY 8 _ Mitterrand re-elected in France.
   MAY 15 _ Soviets begin Afghan troop withdrawal. Kentucky school
bus collision kills 27.
   MAY 19 _ Disturbed woman shoots one child dead, wounds five and
one adult at Winnetka, Ill., elementary school.
   MAY 29 _ Reagan-Gorbachev summit begins in Moscow.
   JUNE 7 _ Dukakis clinches Democratic nomination with victories in
four primaries.
   JUNE 13 _ ``Cigarette lawsuit'' in New Jersey decided in favor of
plantiff.
   JUNE 28 _ Opening day of special Soviet Communist Party
conference that adopts sweeping reforms of Soviet system.
   JULY 3 _ U.S. Navy cruiser Vincennes shoots down Iran Air
jetliner over Persian Gulf, killing all 290 aboard.
   JULY 6 _ Piper Alpha oil platform explodes in North Sea, killing
167.
   JULY 11 _ Terrorist attack on Greek cruise ship kills nine,
wounds 98.
   JULY 13 _ Principles of Angola settlement reached in New York
talks.
   JULY 20 _ Dukakis nominated for president by Democrats.
   JULY 31 _ Hussein resigns Jordan's claim to West Bank.
   AUG. 8 _ Perez de Cueller announces Iran-Iraq cease-fire.
   AUG. 17 _ Bush nominated for president by Republicans. President
Zia of Pakistan, U.S. Ambassador Raphel killed in plane crash.
   AUG. 27 _ Heavy flooding in Bangladesh; at least 1,000 perish.
   AUG. 28 _ Italian precision-flying unit crashes into air show
crowd in West Germany, killing 70.
   AUG. 31 _ Thirteen die in Delta crash at Dallas-Forth Worth
Airport.
   SEPT. 8 _ Firestorm around Old Faithful in continuing summer of
fire in Yellowstone National Park and elsewhere in West.
   SEPT. 12-16 _ Hurricane Gilbert strikes Jamaica, Cayman Islands,
Mexico.
   SEPT. 12 _ West German hostage Rudolf Cordes freed in Beirut.
   SEPT. 17 _ Summer Olympics open in Seoul.
   SEPT. 29 _ Shuttle Discovery launched, resuming U.S. manned space
program.
   OCT. 1 _ In major shakeup, Gorbachev becomes Soviet president,
Gromyko retires.
   OCT. 3 _ Beirut hostage Mithileshwar Singh, U.S. resident, freed.
   OCT. 5 _ President Pinochet loses Chilean referendum.
   OCT. 19-25 _ Hurricane Joan kills 184 in Central America.
   OCT. 20 _ Dodgers defeat Oakland A's to win World Series.
   OCT. 21 _ Deposed Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos and wife,
Imelda, indicted on racketeering charges in New York.
   OCT. 26 _ Trapped whales in Alaskan Arctic freed in combined
U.S.-Soviet effort.
   NOV. 1 _ Israel election, Likud gains slightly.
   NOV. 3 _ Computer virus strikes nationwide research network.
   NOV. 6 _ Soviet dissident Andrei Sakharov arrives in U.S. for
visit.
   NOV. 8 _ Bush-Quayle elected.
   NOV. 15 _ Palestine National Council proclaims independent
Palestinian homeland. Soviet space shuttle Buran makes first flight,
unmanned.
   NOV. 16 _ In Soviet Union, Estonia declares ``sovereignty.''
   NOV. 21 _ Conservatives win Canadian election.
   DEC. 1 _ Supreme Soviet, national parliament, adopts government
reforms.
   DEC. 2 _ Space shuttle Atlantis launched on four-day mission;
Benazir Bhutto becomes Pakistan prime minister.
   DEC. 5 _ PTL founder Jim Bakker indicted on fraud charges.
   DEC. 7 _ Gorbachev, at United Nations, announces troop
reductions. Devastating earthquake in Soviet Armenia; official
estimates of up to 55,000 killed.
   DEC. 8 _ Air Force jet carrying ammunition crashes into
residential area of Remscheid, West Germany, killing 5. Palestinians
in Israel's occupied territories mark one year since beginning of
intefadeh.
   DEC. 11 _ Soviet quake relief plane crashes, killing 79; Mexican
market explosion kills 68.
   DEC 12. _ London triple train crash kills 33; Yugoslav quake
relief plane crashes, killing 7.
   DEC. 13 _ Yasser Arafat speaks to United Nations at session in
Geneva; PTL assets sold for $65 million.
   DEC. 14 _ U.S. announces it will open dialogue with PLO after
Arafat says he will accept Israel.
   DEC. 16 _ U.S. holds first direct talks with PLO; political
extremist Lyndon LaRouche convicted of tax and mail fraud conspiracy.
   DEC. 21 _ Pan Am Boeing 747 crashes in Scotland, killing at least
281 aboard and on the ground; sabotage is suspected. Israel's
right-wing Likud bloc and center-left Labor Party decide to form a
new national unity government. Two Soviet cosmonauts end history's
longest space flight _ a year in orbit.
   DEC. 22 _ South Africa, Cuba and Angola sign accords granting
independence to Namibia, a South African colony, and pledging to
withdraw 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Year-End Editions</NOTE>
